@startuml paak_input_stale_to_access_block_signal_flow
!theme plain
skinparam backgroundColor #FFFFFF
skinparam defaultFontName Arial
skinparam defaultFontSize 11
skinparam sequenceMessageAlign center
skinparam responseMessageBelowArrow true

title PAAK Input Stale To Access Block Signal Flow\n(PAAK freshness loss -> BCM fallback -> door access block)

participant "PAAK freshness /\nvehicle context" as FreshnessCtx #F4F7FB
participant "BCM\nbody access owner" as BCM #E8F7E8
participant "Door control path" as DoorBus #FFF4CC
participant "Observers / panels" as Obs #E8F0FE

== Freshness Loss ==

FreshnessCtx -> BCM : gPaakRxMs / gVehicleRxMs
BCM -> BCM : paakInputStale = recentTick(PAAK) ? 0 : 1
BCM -> BCM : if paakInputStale == 1\nthen clear paakState / authLevel / proximity
note right of BCM
Representative freshness behavior
- paakInputStale = 1 when PAAK input is not recent
- access-related state is zeroed before command decision
end note

== Access Block ==

BCM -> BCM : recompute DoorControlCmd after stale clear
BCM -> BCM : stale path prevents valid access-open condition
BCM -> DoorBus : frmDoorControlMsg\nDoorControlCmd = 0
note right of BCM
Representative blocked output
- DoorControlCmd falls back to closed
- no access-driven open command is published
end note

== Visibility ==

DoorBus -> Obs : blocked access readback /\nbody command health trace

note over FreshnessCtx, Obs
Representative runtime chain
1. PAAK freshness is lost
2. BCM clears access credentials and proximity context
3. Door open command is blocked on the body command path
4. Observers expose stale access and blocked-door behavior
end note

@enduml
